metadata.name: Beyond #191
metadata.description:
This generative art token is a collaboration between artist Jaali Bandar and the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. Jaali Bandar’s genesis fxhash project “Mona Lisa Overdrive” was one of the first NFTs acquired for the permanent collection. It was showcased at the NFT Museum’s #Cryptografik exhibition throughout the Spring of 2022. 

Jaali Bandar’s work quickly evolved to become fully immersive and interactive multimedia experiences (see Terra, What on Earth? and Terra Nova). In an effort to bring our worlds closer together, the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC reached out to Jaali Bandar of Bangalore, India to collaborate. This artwork explores the ethereal space where the real and the virtual meet. This is Beyond.  

We share 33% of future royalties with the original minters in an effort to encourage the promotion of fxhash artists and raise awareness of generative art on the blockchain. We want this art to spread far and wide. Thank you for your support in helping us accomplish this goal.


Token Details:

Beyond
Collab by Jaali Bandar x NFTMuseumSC
June 2022
fxhash Compliant NFT


Artist Bio: 

Jaali Bandar is an artist exploring the tech landscape in its anthropomorphic capacity as our collective moves towards a post-human condition. Coming from a design background he is exploring speculative fiction at the interactions of the meta, material and the virtual to create fictional representations using imagery, simulations and experiences.  


Artist Statement

As we let ourselves be overwhelmed by this omnipresent technological feedback, we change rapidly in more ways than we can fathom. As we approach the technological singularity, the question I ask is that how far can we see? As we complete the process of shifting our decision making burdens to the machines, all that remains are automated landscapes of our post-human desires and fragments of memories from a distant past. 

Beyond explores automated human exclusion zones with occasional glimpses of forgotten artifacts of the previous generation as a generative artwork. Diffusion reaction systems have this uncanny ability to morph perspectives as a function of visual feedback loops on the basis of visual inputs with varying degrees of control. 


Interactions:

- Press ‘p’ to show/hide cursor
- Press 's' to save .png 



Additional Credits and Attributions:

- Coded using Cables.gl : https://cables.gl/


About the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC:

Established in October of 2021, the mission of the Non-Fungible Token Museum is to provide a physical and virtual space for NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition in an effort to help our communities benefit from emerging blockchain technologies. Learn more at www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: Pride Month Tribute #20
metadata.description:
Sentimentio’s genesis NFT collection centers around celebration.

Capped at just 31 editions, it’s a fusion of coding and data to generate artworks that reflect societal sentiments 
towards the LGBTQ+ community and Pride Month over a three-year period.

Data collected from 100K online articles are transformed into artistic traits that express emotions and sentiments through shapes, color, and movement.
 
Sentiment score, ranging from -1 to +1, indicates whether the overall sentiment of articles is positive, negative, or neutral. Represented visually in the background, shades of white signify positive sentiment scores (0 to 1) whereas backgrounds with dark tones reflect negative sentiment scores (-1 to 0).

Emotions are key to our generative artworks.

The hue of the dots in the Pride Month Tribute NFT collection represents the following emotions.

-happiness: pink, yellow
-anger: red
-sadness: purple
-fear: blue
-surprise: green
-disgust: olive

Feelings can be more intense than others in the different time periods covered by our data. The more powerful a particular emotion, the more prominent that color will be in the artwork.

Other aspects such as the size of the dots or their movements are defined by the beautiful randomness of the code.

#CodingIsArt #sentimentio

metadata.name: Amplitude #133
metadata.description:
Amplitude is a study in depth. Waves travel across the frame using Perlin noise to guide its modulation. Allowing slight variations to occur in each layer. Sometimes the waves are added to the frame and sometimes they are subtracted. Resulting in dramatically different visual appearances. 

Like most of my work this piece is carefully designed to also exist IRL as a 12 layer laser carved woodcut. 
https://alleditions.art/p/amplitude

Arrow keys - adjust the perspective

DESIGNED FOR IRL
Shift P - for a PNG
Shift E - to explode the layers
Shift S - for an SVG

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #484
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma // https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Ocean Currents #20
metadata.description:
I wanted to depict the beauty and movement of ocean currents, inspired by NASA's aerial images of currents leaving and entering the ocean. I combined elements of painting, the release of warm and cool colors and images of twisting and moving ocean currents into creative visual pieces that evoke a sense of the dynamic nature of the ocean.
Each piece often features vibrant colors and fluid shapes that mimic water's flow to create intricate patterns that resemble swirling currents.
With this art form, I not only celebrate the aesthetic appeal of oceans, but also raise awareness of their importance in supporting marine life. Also reminding us of the interconnectedness of our planet's ecosystems in order to motivate us to appreciate and protect our oceans.
Whether displayed in homes, offices, or public spaces, Ocean Currents will add calm and natural beauty to any setting. It serves as a visual reminder of the power and majesty of the ocean while inviting viewers to reflect on their connection to the natural world.
Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.description:
I come from a family of gemstones merchants going back a hundred years. In fact, I’m of the first generation who did not pursue the career. The carat series is my way to pay homage to this heritage.

The 0.20 carat collection is dedicated to my mother. Her lifetime passion for precious stones and their beauty inspired my aesthetic sensibility and led me to become an artist.

metadata.name: Holy Moly #18
metadata.description:
The idea for this project came from a common drawing exercise where different shapes and shading are used to create the illusion of depth. Here I'm using four layers containing various types of holes. Some are recognizable primitive shapes but others are organic in form or distorted. There are ten features reported that affect the character of each output.

To change the resolution:
1. Click on the image
2. Use the keys 2-8 to change resolution, '2' will produce a 2000 x 2000 image (default), '3' a 3000 x 3000 image etc
3. Once generated press 'S' to save as a png

Jeff Clark
December 2022
--------------------------
All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using vanilla javascript except for:

- perlin.js from https://codepen.io/sixsided/pen/emxxea.js
